Body condition did not differ notably between virus-positive and virus-negative FY birds sampled on the same day (p>0.05, Mann-Whitney Wilcoxon test), except for during the third week of July during 2009 (p = 0.046) and 2010 (p = 0.0004), when virus-positive birds had lower body condition. This suggests that, overall, H13 and H16 virus infections are nonpathogenic for BHGU. Previous studies found no clinical signs (
 
  8
 ) or histological lesions (
 
  9
 ) in gulls naturally infected with H13 or H16 virus. No notable differences in virus prevalence were found related to gender, no consistent differences in virus prevalence were found related to capture method, and no AIVs in dead BHGU were detected outside epidemics (
 Technical Appendix).
